{
  "texts": [
    "If the functor is an inclusion of a full subcategory with a certain condition on hom sets, then the kernel of the induced map on abstract Burnside rings is easily identified.",
    "Epiorbital categories of epimorphismsWe will now provide an example of the abstract Burnside ring machinery of Section 2 by choosing the finite skeletal category to be the (skeleton of the) category Epi ≤𝑑 of epimorphisms of finite sets of cardinality at most 𝑑.",
    "In the case 𝑑 = 2, there is an equivalence between the category of epimorphisms and the obit category Orb 𝐶 2 of the group 𝐶 2 of two elements.",
    "In general, however, the category Epi ≤𝑑 is not equivalent to the orbit category of a finite group.Definition 3.1.",
    "For each 𝑑 ≥ 1, define the rational Goodwillie Burnside ring 𝐴 Q (𝑑) to be the rational abstract Burnside ring associated to the category Epi ≤𝑑.This terminology follows [ABHS25, Section 8]."
  ]
}